  "text": "DNA base composition. Cultures were grown as described for the glucose fermentation experiments except that the medium and inoculum were increased sixfold and the gas phase was nitrogen. Growth was measured turbidimetrically on samples withdrawn through a port in the gassing head, under a flow of nitrogen. Cultures in the late-exponential phase of growth (24 h) were harvested by centrifugation and washed twice with saline/EDTA solution (containing 0.15 M-NaCl and 0.1 M-EDTA, pH 8.0). Bacteria were disrupted in a press (Hughes, 1951) and then heated at 70 \"C for 15 min in saline/EDTA containing 3% (w/v) sodium dodecyl sulphate. The method of Marmur (1961) was then used with the following modifications. Three ribonuclease treatments were given at 37 \"C for 0.5 h, using ribonuclease TI in addition to ribonuclease I [CITATION_1] . After each treatment, NaCl and heat-treated protease (Sigma type VI) (Hotta & Bassel, 1965) were added for I h at 45 \"C (I mg protease preparation per ml nucleic acid solution for the first treatments; 100 ,ug ml-l for the second and third treatments). After the first two protease treatments a single deproteinization was done but after the third treatment the procedure of Marmur was followed, with further deproteinization and one final precipitation using propan-2-01. The precipitated DNA was dried with ethanol and dissolved in 0.15 M-NaCl plus 0.015 M-trisodium citrate.",
